(76, 1, '2012-01-09 15:55:59', '2012-01-09 15:55:59', 'Jeffrey A. Messer serves as an independent investment advisor in Indiana and Michigan.  Prior to coming to Umbaugh, he worked in the banking industry for 22 years with an emphasis on public funds banking and investments.\r\n\r\nAt Umbaugh Cash Advisory Services he provides investment and banking services to municipalities throughout Indiana and Michigan, including assisting municipalities with the investment of their municipal bond proceeds and operating funds.  \r\n\r\nJeff joined Umbaugh in 2005.  His group [or UCAS] provides independent advice on investments for local units of government throughout Indiana and Michigan in excess of $350 million in assets; and is responsible for bank analysis and RFPs for banking services for many Umbaugh clients. \r\n\r\nHe writes a weekly market update for UCAS clients and often gives presentations at various association conferences in Indiana and Michigan on investment and banking related topics.  \r\n\r\nHe is a graduate of Indiana University.', 'Jeffrey A. Messer', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'jeffrey-a-messer', '', '', '2012-01-26 18:40:52', '2012-01-26 18:40:52', '', 0, 'http://cashadvisory.umbaugh.com/?post_type=partner&#038;p=76', 0, 'partner', '', 0),
(95, 1, '2012-01-09 14:09:46', '2012-01-09 14:09:46', '<p>At UCAS, we understand that municipalities continue to face budget challenges and are increasingly being asked to do more with less.  Developing an efficient banking and investment program that not only protects your funds, but also provides an adequate return is no easy task.</p>\r\n<p>This is where our experienced team at UCAS comes in to assist our municipal clients with professional investment advice.  When it comes to investing public dollars, we focus on safety, liquidity and return, in that order.  Our core business is assisting our clients in developing short-term structured portfolios for their bond proceeds and operating funds. Our goal is to assist our clients in safely generating additional interest earnings for their budgets.<p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>We provide the following services:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Bond Proceeds Investment Advisory</strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>Operating Funds Investment Advisory</strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>Banking Request for Proposal Services</strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>Construction Fund Administration Services</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', 'About Us', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '4-revision-5', '', '', '2012-01-09 14:09:46', '2012-01-09 14:09:46', '', 4, 'http://cashadvisory.umbaugh.com/4-revision-5', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(77, 1, '2011-11-30 15:57:34', '2011-11-30 15:57:34', '<p style="text-align: left;"><em>Ten Steps to Investing Public Funds </em></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">When the banking industry was reeling in the first wave of the financial crisis of 2008, both the public and government leaders clamored for more regulation and more protection for investors and depositors.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">Congress heeded the public’s outcry, producing a raft of new regulations. The Dodd-Frank Act alone mandates 250 new regulations and 70 studies and created 13 new agencies, including the Financial Stability Oversight Council.   The regulations impose higher capital requirements on the larger financial institutions and will ultimately result in higher costs for all banks.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">What happens when the cost of banking goes up?  Banks will be faced with lower margins or may very well pass those costs along to their clients.  But hopefully the additional costs and the effort required to comply with new regulations are a worthwhile investment to gain the new protections that have been put in place.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">Although the 10 steps to investing public funds outlined below are good advice in any situation, they have become even more important in the wake of financial industry turmoil and increased regulation.</p>\r\n\r\n<ol style="text-align: left;">\r\n	<li><strong>Identify your objectives </strong>–<strong> </strong>Just as you would in a personal investment portfolio, set goals for what you’re trying to achieve, but this time you’re using the public’s money.  You need to assess how much risk you’re willing to tolerate and consider how liquid you need the investments to be. Think about your staff size and abilities.  What is your capacity to oversee the investments?   What amount of fluctuation can you tolerate and still meet your budget requirements? </li>\r\n	<li><strong>Develop an investment policy – </strong>Now that you know your objectives, create a policy that helps you get there, by defining eligible investments, risks, management oversight, reporting, authorized financial institutions and maturity parameters.<strong> </strong></li>\r\n	<li><strong>Develop operational systems and procedures – </strong>Create written procedures to provide consistency, ensure compliance with public funds laws and describe who is responsible for various duties.<strong> </strong></li>\r\n	<li><strong>Prepare an investment cash budget – </strong>With a goal of determining “core” balances, identify dollars that can be invested for longer periods of time.  These funds may include debt service reserve, rainy day, capital and various other funds.  If you can invest them longer, it is possible to take advantage of higher interest rates.<strong> </strong><strong> </strong></li>\r\n	<li><strong>Analyze current market rates and develop an investment strategy – </strong>Contact your local banker, broker or adviser and ask about the current interest rate environment.  Ask what the yield curve looks like and about interest rate trends.  Get your adviser’s recommendation on how much and how long to invest. </li>\r\n	<li><strong>Determine appropriate investments – </strong>The State has regulations and options for appropriate investments.  These will be covered more fully in the next article.<strong> </strong></li>\r\n	<li><strong>Track investment results – </strong>As earnings reports come in; compare your earnings to your budget expectations.  Also compare your investment results to what would have happened if you left all dollars in your bank sweep account.<strong> </strong></li>\r\n	<li><strong>Report results -- </strong>Prepare a report once or twice a year so you are ready to report to your local board, council or commissions.  Periodic reporting shows you and others the value of a more structured investment program. </li>\r\n	<li><strong>Monitor and make changes as necessary – </strong>Some decisions you make now may not work as financial conditions change.  Monitor your results to ensure cash budget requirements are being met and to evaluate if changing market conditions should alter your future decisions regarding amounts and length of time for investments.<strong>  </strong></li>\r\n	<li><strong>Institutionalize the process – </strong>Once you develop a structured and formalized system for investing your public funds, execute this process year after year to improve your investment performance and add additional dollars to your budget.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">Next month, we’ll cover investment alternatives available under Michigan Compiled Law (MCL).</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;"><em>If you have questions regarding the new banking regulations or determining effective investment processes and options, please contact us at </em><a href="mailto:footnotes@umbaugh.com"><em>footnotes@umbaugh.com</em></a><em>.</em></p>', 'The Impact of Banking Regulations, Part 1', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'the-impact-of-banking-regulations-part-1', '', '', '2012-01-09 16:51:26', '2012-01-09 16:51:26', '', 0, 'http://cashadvisory.umbaugh.com/?p=77', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(78, 1, '2012-01-09 15:58:37', '2012-01-09 15:58:37', '<p style="text-align: left;"><em>Ten Steps to Investing Public Funds </em></p>\n<p style="text-align: left;">When the banking industry was reeling in the first wave of the financial crisis of 2008, both the public and government leaders clamored for more regulation and more protection for investors and depositors.</p>\n<p style="text-align: left;">Congress heeded the public’s outcry, producing a raft of new regulations. The Dodd-Frank Act alone mandates 250 new regulations and 70 studies and created 13 new agencies, including the Financial Stability Oversight Council.   The regulations impose higher capital requirements on the larger financial institutions and will ultimately result in higher costs for all banks.</p>\n<p style="text-align: left;">What happens when the cost of banking goes up?  Banks will be faced with lower margins or may very well pass those costs along to their clients.  But hopefully the additional costs and the effort required to comply with new regulations are a worthwhile investment to gain the new protections that have been put in place.</p>\n<p style="text-align: left;">Although the 10 steps to investing public funds outlined below are good advice in any situation, they have become even more important in the wake of financial industry turmoil and increased regulation.</p>\n\n<ol style="text-align: left;">\n	<li><strong>Identify your objectives </strong>–<strong> </strong>Just as you would in a personal investment portfolio, set goals for what you’re trying to achieve, but this time you’re using the public’s money.  You need to assess how much risk you’re willing to tolerate and consider how liquid you need the investments to be. Think about your staff size and abilities.  What is your capacity to oversee the investments?   What amount of fluctuation can you tolerate and still meet your budget requirements? </li>\n	<li><strong>Develop an investment policy – </strong>Now that you know your objectives, create a policy that helps you get there, by defining eligible investments, risks, management oversight, reporting, authorized financial institutions and maturity parameters.<strong> </strong></li>\n	<li><strong>Develop operational systems and procedures – </strong>Create written procedures to provide consistency, ensure compliance with public funds laws and describe who is responsible for various duties.<strong> </strong></li>\n	<li><strong>Prepare an investment cash budget – </strong>With a goal of determining “core” balances, identify dollars that can be invested for longer periods of time.  These funds may include debt service reserve, rainy day, capital and various other funds.  If you can invest them longer, it is possible to take advantage of higher interest rates.<strong> </strong><strong> </strong></li>\n	<li><strong>Analyze current market rates and develop an investment strategy – </strong>Contact your local banker, broker or adviser and ask about the current interest rate environment.  Ask what the yield curve looks like and about interest rate trends.  Get your adviser’s recommendation on how much and how long to invest. </li>\n	<li><strong>Determine appropriate investments – </strong>The State has regulations and options for appropriate investments.  These will be covered more fully in the next article.<strong> </strong></li>\n	<li><strong>Track investment results – </strong>As earnings reports come in; compare your earnings to your budget expectations.  Also compare your investment results to what would have happened if you left all dollars in your bank sweep account.<strong> </strong></li>\n	<li><strong>Report results -- </strong>Prepare a report once or twice a year so you are ready to report to your local board, council or commissions.  Periodic reporting shows you and others the value of a more structured investment program. </li>\n	<li><strong>Monitor and make changes as necessary – </strong>Some decisions you make now may not work as financial conditions change.  Monitor your results to ensure cash budget requirements are being met and to evaluate if changing market conditions should alter your future decisions regarding amounts and length of time for investments.<strong>  </strong></li>\n	<li><strong>Institutionalize the process – </strong>Once you develop a structured and formalized system for investing your public funds, execute this process year after year to improve your investment performance and add additional dollars to your budget.</li>\n</ol>\n<p style="text-align: left;">Next month, we’ll cover investment alternatives available under Michigan Compiled Law (MCL).</p>\n<p style="text-align: left;"><em>If you have questions regarding the new banking regulations or determining effective investment processes and options, please contact us at </em><a href="mailto:footnotes@umbaugh.com"><em>footnotes@umbaugh.com</em></a><em>.</em></p>', 'The Impact of Banking Regulations, Part 1', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '77-revision', '', '', '2012-01-09 15:58:37', '2012-01-09 15:58:37', '', 77, 'http://cashadvisory.umbaugh.com/77-revision', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
