(81, 1, '2011-10-05 16:42:05', '2011-10-05 16:42:05', 'In the last issue of Footnotes, we outlined the <a href="http://www.umbaugh.com/banking-regulations-impact-pt-2">Ten Steps</a> to Investing Public Funds.  Step 6 is to Determine Appropriate Investments.  Consider expanding your investments by looking at all the safe options the public funds code allows. As the Indiana General Assembly reacted to the need to protect investors and depositors in these turbulent times for the financial industry, it created additional alternatives for investing public funds.  Following is a list of eligible investments described in Indiana code 5-13-9.\r\n\r\n<strong>Liquid investments</strong> – Liquid investments can be immediately turned into cash.  These are checking, savings, sweep, money market mutual funds, LGIP and joint investment funds.\r\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;"><strong>Deposit Accounts</strong> (checking, savings, sweep,) – Your goal for these funds should be to maximize interest and minimize fees.  Calculate your net rate of return, balancing that with the reserve requirements and any high transaction charges and FDIC assessment fees.  These funds have the advantage of being insured by FDIC and Indiana’s Public Deposit Insurance Fund (PDIF) or the new collateral requirements described in our <a href="http://www.umbaugh.com/banking-regulations-impact-pt1">September 7</a> issue.</p>\r\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;"><strong>Repo Sweeps</strong> – These accounts (Indiana Code 5-13-9-3) sweep dollars “off balance sheet” at the end of every day then collateralize your money with agency or treasury securities.</p>\r\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;"><strong>Local Government Investment Pool (LGIP) – </strong>You may find it advantageous to participate in the Indiana State Treasurer’s Trust Indiana Fund created by Indiana Code 5-13-9-11.  You can access funds the same day you request them.  The Trust Indiana Fund invests in Indiana-eligible investments and 50% of the fund must be in Indiana bank deposits, but it can also invest in treasuries, agencies and commercial paper.  No resolution is needed to deposit funds in Trust Indiana.</p>\r\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;"><strong>Interlocal Agreements </strong>– Authorized by Indiana Code 36-1-7, political subdivisions can pass a resolution to participate in an interlocal cooperative agreement. These generally work like the LGIP and can only use investments eligible under 5-13-9.</p>\r\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;"><strong>Money Market Mutual Funds</strong> – As described in Indiana Code 5-13-9-2.5, these portfolios are limited to direct obligations of the U.S., a federal agency, a federal instrumentality or federal government-sponsored enterprise or repurchase agreements fully collateralized by such obligations.  There are minimum standards for credit ratings, and you may purchase them through your local bank or broker. </p>\r\n<strong>Short-term and intermediate investments</strong> have maturities of 30 days to two years.  These include CDs, CDARS, treasuries, agencies and municipal securities.\r\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;"><strong>Government Securities – </strong>These securities are backed by the full faith and credit of the United States Treasury, or are fully guaranteed by the U.S.  and issued by the Treasury, a federal agency, a federal instrumentality or a federal-government-sponsored enterprise. They may be purchased through a local bank or broker.</p>\r\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;"><strong>Municipal Securities – </strong>The ability to invest in municipal securities was added in 2010. These securities are issued by an Indiana local governmental entity, a quasi-governmental entity related to the State, or a unit of government, municipal corporation or special taxing district in Indiana.  The investment is described in Indiana Code 5-13-9-2 and requires that the issuer has not defaulted on any of its obligations within 20 years preceding the date of purchase.  They may be purchased through a local bank or broker. </p>\r\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;"><strong>Certificates of Deposit and Deposit Accounts – </strong>State law requires the investing officer to obtain quotes from each designated depository in the political subdivision.  In 2010, a section was added allowing the investing officer to place the deposit in the depository quoting the second or third highest rate of interest.  Also the political subdivision’s board may pass a resolution allowing it to use Indiana banks outside the subdivision.  This can be a valuable alternative if local banks are not interested in bidding on CDs. </p>\r\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;"><strong>Certificate of Deposit Account Registry Service (CDARS) – </strong>This<strong> </strong>safe investment alternative for local governments was added in 2010.  To use this option, your Board must pass a resolution or ordinance that allows it to use CDARS as an authorized investment.  Many banks in Indiana are members of the CDARS network, and this form of investment is fully insured by FDIC.</p>\r\nOnce you determine appropriate investments, continue with the remaining steps to investing public funds to make the process work for you on an ongoing basis.\r\n\r\nBanks will continue to face regulatory challenges at the state and federal level, but by developing a sound investment and banking program, you can identify opportunities to safely increase your net interest earnings. \r\n\r\n<em>If you have questions or need help with complying with new banking regulations or determining effective investment processes and options, please contact us at <a href="mailto:footnotes@umbaugh.com">footnotes@umbaugh.com</a>.</em>', 'The Impact of State and Federal Banking Regulations, Part 3', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'the-impact-of-state-and-federal-banking-regulations-part-3', '', '\nhttp://www.umbaugh.com/banking-regulations-impact-pt-2', '2012-01-09 16:42:43', '2012-01-09 16:42:43', '', 0, 'http://cashadvisory.umbaugh.com/?p=81', 0, 'post', '', 0),
