 you can invest them longer, it is possible to take advantage of higher interest rates.<strong> </strong><strong> </strong></li>\n	<li><strong>Analyze current market rates and develop an investment strategy – </strong>Contact your local banker, broker or adviser and ask about the current interest rate environment.  Ask what the yield curve looks like and about interest rate trends.  Get your adviser’s recommendation on how much and how long to invest. </li>\n	<li><strong>Determine appropriate investments – </strong>The State has both new regulations and new options for appropriate investments.  These will be covered more fully in the next article in this series.<strong> </strong></li>\n	<li><strong>Track investment results – </strong>As earnings reports come in, compare your earnings to your budget expectations.  Also compare your investment results to what would have happened if you left all dollars in your bank sweep account.<strong> </strong></li>\n	<li><strong>Report results -- </strong>Prepare a report once or twice a year so you are ready to report to your local board or the State Board of Accounts.  Periodic reporting shows you and others the value of a more structured investment program. </li>\n	<li><strong>Monitor and make changes as necessary – </strong>Some decisions you make now may not work as financial conditions change.  Monitor your results to ensure cash budget requirements are being met and to evaluate if changing market conditions should alter your future decisions regarding amounts and length of time for investments.</li>\n	<li><strong>Institutionalize the process – </strong>Once you develop a structured and formalized system for investing your public funds, execute this process year after year to improve your investment performance and add additional dollars to your budget.<strong></strong></li>\n</ol>\n<p style="text-align: left;"><strong> </strong>In the next installment of this series, we’ll cover investment alternatives now available under Indiana code.</p>\n<p style="text-align: left;"><em>If you have questions regarding the new banking regulations or determining effective investment processes and options, please contact us at <a href="mailto:footnotes@umbaugh.com">footnotes@umbaugh.com</a>.</em></p>', 'The Impact of State and Federal Banking Regulations, Part 2', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '83-revision', '', '', '2012-01-09 16:43:19', '2012-01-09 16:43:19', '', 83, 'http://cashadvisory.umbaugh.com/83-revision', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(85, 1, '2011-09-07 16:44:15', '2011-09-07 16:44:15', '<p style="text-align: left;"><em>First article in a series</em></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">When the banking industry was reeling in the first wave of the financial crisis of 2008, both the public and government leaders clamored for more regulation and more protection for investors and depositors.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">Congress and the Indiana General Assembly heeded the public’s outcry, producing a raft of new regulations. The Dodd-Frank Act alone mandates 250 new regulations and 70 studies and created 13 new agencies, including the Financial Stability Oversight Council.   The regulations impose higher capital requirements on the larger financial institutions and will ultimately result in higher costs for all banks.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">What happens when the cost of banking goes up?  Banks will be faced with lower margins or may very well pass those costs along to their clients.  But hopefully the additional costs and the effort required to comply with new regulations are a worthwhile investment to gain the new protections that have been put in place.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">Long before the current financial crisis, Indiana created the Indiana Board for Depositories, an independent body created to insure the safekeeping and prompt payment of all public funds deposited in an approved depository.  The Indiana Board for Depositories maintains and operates the Public Deposit Insurance Fund (PDIF), which provides additional insurance for Indiana public funds not covered by insurance from any federal deposit insurance agency.  Although the PDIF grew to $300 million, the banking crisis illustrated a need for another solution to protect public funds.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">The solution came in the form of new rules for collateralization covered in P.L. 115-2010.  The new rules establish a method of placing banks in three categories based on their Highline Rating, which is a predictor of a financial institutions health and potential for failure. </p>\r\n\r\n<ul style="text-align: left;">\r\n	<li>Banks in the lowest category (those with Highline Rankings from 0 to 19) are required to deliver U.S. Treasury Securities and agency securities to the State of Indiana sufficient to cover 100% of the amount of their public funds on deposit.  Approximately 10% percent of Indiana banks are in this category. </li>\r\n	<li>Banks in the middle category (those with Highline Rankings from 20 to 39) must pledge or set aside U.S. Treasury and agency securities sufficient to cover 50% of the amount of their public fund deposits. Approximately 16% of Indiana banks are in this group. </li>\r\n	<li>Banks in the highest category (with Highline Rankings from 40 to 99) do not have special requirements, and this group constitutes approximately 73% of Indiana banks.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">With these new protections, plus FDIC insurance and PDIF insurance, local governments can sleep at night knowing that their funds are safe with their local banks.  If your local bank is no longer accepting deposits of public funds, however, this new law may be the reason why.  The cost of providing the collateral to accept public funds may now be too much for them, especially when you add Dodd-Frank requirements and an economy still hovering on the edge of recession.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">In later installments of this series, we’ll cover 10 steps to investing public funds and eligible investment alternatives now available under Indiana code.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;"><em>If you have questions or need help with complying with new banking regulations or determining effective investment processes and options, please contact us at <a href="mailto:footnotes@umbaugh.com">footnotes@umbaugh.com</a>.</em></p>', 'The Impact of State and Federal Banking Regulations, Part 1', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'the-impact-of-state-and-federal-banking-regulations-part-1', '', '', '2012-01-09 16:44:56', '2012-01-09 16:44:56', '', 0, 'http://cashadvisory.umbaugh.com/?p=85', 0, 'post', '', 0),
