ting, which is a predictor of a financial institutions health and potential for failure. </p>\r\n\r\n<ul style="text-align: left;">\r\n	<li>Banks in the lowest category (those with Highline Rankings from 0 to 19) are required to deliver U.S. Treasury Securities and agency securities to the State of Indiana sufficient to cover 100% of the amount of their public funds on deposit.  Approximately 10% percent of Indiana banks are in this category. </li>\r\n	<li>Banks in the middle category (those with Highline Rankings from 20 to 39) must pledge or set aside U.S. Treasury and agency securities sufficient to cover 50% of the amount of their public fund deposits. Approximately 16% of Indiana banks are in this group. </li>\r\n	<li>Banks in the highest category (with Highline Rankings from 40 to 99) do not have special requirements, and this group constitutes approximately 73% of Indiana banks.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">With these new protections, plus FDIC insurance and PDIF insurance, local governments can sleep at night knowing that their funds are safe with their local banks.  If your local bank is no longer accepting deposits of public funds, however, this new law may be the reason why.  The cost of providing the collateral to accept public funds may now be too much for them, especially when you add Dodd-Frank requirements and an economy still hovering on the edge of recession.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">In later installments of this series, we’ll cover 10 steps to investing public funds and eligible investment alternatives now available under Indiana code.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;"><em>If you have questions or need help with complying with new banking regulations or determining effective investment processes and options, please contact us at <a href="mailto:footnotes@umbaugh.com">footnotes@umbaugh.com</a>.</em></p>', 'The Impact of State and Federal Banking Regulations, Part 1', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '85-revision-2', 